# Adding Navigation to your React Component

To make your onClick event navigate to another TSX component, you need to use a routing solution. In React applications, this is typically handled by React Router.

## Using React Router

Here's how you can implement this:

### 1. Install React Router if you haven't already:

```bash
npm install react-router-dom
```

### 2. Set up your router in your main application file (like App.tsx):

```tsx
import { BrowserRouter, Routes, Route } from 'react-router-dom';
import YourCurrentComponent from './components/YourCurrentComponent';
import YourTargetComponent from './components/YourTargetComponent';

function App() {
  return (
    <BrowserRouter>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/" element={<YourCurrentComponent />} />
        <Route path="/target" element={<YourTargetComponent />} />
      </Routes>
    </BrowserRouter>
  );
}
```

### 3. Update your button to use navigation:

```tsx
import { useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom';

function YourCurrentComponent() {
  const navigate = useNavigate();

  return (
    <div style={{ display: "flex", gap: "0.5rem" }}>
      <Button
        variant="primary"
        onClick={() => navigate('/target')}
      >
        Go to Target Component
      </Button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Alternative Approaches

### Using Link Component

Instead of a Button with onClick, you could use React Router's Link component:

```tsx
import { Link } from 'react-router-dom';

<Link to="/target">
  <Button variant="primary">Go to Target Component</Button>
</Link>
```

### For Next.js Applications

If you're using Next.js, you would use its router:

```tsx
import { useRouter } from 'next/router';

function YourComponent() {
  const router = useRouter();

  return (
    <Button 
      variant="primary"
      onClick={() => router.push('/target')}
    >
      Go to Target Component
    </Button>
  );
}
```

Choose the approach that best fits your application's setup and routing solution.
Is there an approach without touching the main.tsx?
# Navigation Without Modifying main.tsx

Yes, you can implement component navigation without touching your main.tsx file. Here are several approaches:

## 1. Using Conditional Rendering

This approach keeps everything within your current component structure by conditionally rendering different components:

```tsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import TargetComponent from './TargetComponent';

function YourCurrentComponent() {
  const [currentView, setCurrentView] = useState('main');

  if (currentView === 'target') {
    return <TargetComponent onBack={() => setCurrentView('main')} />;
  }

  return (
    <div style={{ display: "flex", gap: "0.5rem" }}>
      <Button
        variant="primary"
        onClick={() => setCurrentView('target')}
      >
        Go to Target Component
      </Button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

